emonstrates that despite the multiplicity of influences that help shape our concept of race, common themes prevail. Examining legal, political, social, and cultural sources related to immigration, she advances the theory that our understanding of race is socially constructed in relational ways-that is, in correspondence to other groups. Molina introduces and explains her central theory, racial scripts, which highlights the ways in which the lives of racialized groups are linked across time and space and thereby affect one another. How Race Is Made in America also shows that these racial scripts are easily adopted and adapted to apply to different racial groups.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aCitizenshipxHistoryx20th centuryxUnited States. 0aCitizenshipzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aDeportationxHistoryx20th centuryxUnited States. 0aDeportationzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aImmigrantsxHistoryx20th centuryxUnited States. 0aImmigrantszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aMexican AmericansxCivil rightsxHistoryx20th century. 0aMexican AmericansxCivil rightsxHistoryy20th century. 0aMexican AmericansxSocial conditionsx20th century. 0aMexican AmericansxSocial conditionsy20th century. 0aRace discriminationxHistoryx20th centuryxUnited States. 0aRace discriminationzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / United States / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066334108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311062111208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUCal Press eBook Package 2014-2016z978311065748740uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520957190423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520957190.jpg  a978-3-11-062